Hypothesis 1

friends_vs_happiness <-responses %>%
select(Number.of.friends, Happiness.in.life) %>%
arrange(desc(Number.of.friends))

plot(jitter(Number.of.friends)~jitter(Happiness.in.life), data=friends_vs_happiness)

Happier individuals are more likely to have more friends.

Hypothesis #2:

gender_vs_happiness <-responses %>%
    select(Gender, Happiness.in.life) %>% na.omit()

                                            boxplot(Happiness.in.life~Gender, data=gender_vs_happiness)

Happiness does not seem to be related to gender.

Hypothesis 3:

happiness_vs_age <-responses %>% na.omit()%>%
    select(Age, Happiness.in.life) %>% group_by(Age)  %>%
summarise(avg_happiness = mean(Happiness.in.life))


plot(avg_happiness~Age, data=happiness_vs_age)

It seems that younger individuals are more likely to be unhappy in comparison to the older participants sampled who are much happier.

names(responses) #Hypothesis 4:

weight_vs_age <-responses %>%
    select(Weight, Age) %>% na.omit()


plot(jitter(Weight)~ jitter(Age) , data=weight_vs_age)

It looks like age generally increased in moving from 15 years old to 20. While there were a few outliers in older populations that had much higher weights than the norm, most of the older individuals had weights that were on par with the younger participants.

Hypothesis 5:

socializing_vs_age <-responses %>%
    select(Socializing, Age) %>% na.omit()

plot(jitter(Socializing)~ jitter(Age) , data=socializing_vs_age)

Younter individuals are more likely to strongly enjoy socializing relative to older participants.

Hypothesis 6:

opera_vs_age<- responses %>%
    select(Opera, Age) %>% na.omit()

plot(jitter(Opera)~ jitter(Age) , data=opera_vs_age)

It seems like a larger percentage of older participants enjoyed opera relative to the younger individuals, so according to this data set, opera appreciaiton increases with age.
